english:
  title: Crossing the Plank Road
  author: Kim Siseup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Mountains curve and wind back; waters slip askew.
    Where cooking smoke rises, there dwells a home.
    Before the wind, swallows winnow the fine mist—
    After rain, duckling chicks tread the delicate sand.

    Distant peaks with their ridges block the thousand-mile view.
    A broken bridge leans beside the flowers of one ravine.

    Long have I known the traveler's heart cannot be soothed,
    So why not simply spend the years in leisured ease?
  footnotes:
    - The 'plank road' likely refers to a precarious mountain passage, symbolizing life's difficult journey
    - The contrast between the vivid natural details of the first quatrain and the philosophical resignation of the final couplet reflects the poet's meditation on acceptance versus struggle
